title: For Sale:  UNION SWITCH & SIGNAL (US&S) ~ 1911A1 U.S. ARMY OUTSTANDING ORIGINAL PISTOL.
postcontent: Here's one of the harder to find WWII .45 automatics. This 1911A1 was manufactured by Union Switch & Signal in 1943. Of the nearly 2-million 1911A1's manufactured during the Second World War, only 55,000 were manufactured by US&S. Only the fabled Singer is rarer. This pistol is in excellent shape and appears to be 100% original and genuine. The frame is properly marked with the circled RCD acceptance found only on the US&S production. Neither the frame nor the slide have the "P" proof which is correct for the earlier US&S pistols. All of the various parts are correct for a US&S including the coarse checkered hammer, finely knurled mainspring housing, blued trigger, "concentric circle" barrel bushing, HS barrel, etc. The original Dulite blue finish is fully original and in excellent overall condition with some normal expected handling wear and a very slight touch of patina to the left side of the slide. There is no significant rust and absolutely no pitting. The frame's bullet ramp is milled in the white, as is correct for an original finish pistol. I'd grade the original finish at about 96-97% overall. The original Keyes Fibre grips are in excellent shape, matching the pistol. The mechanics are in perfect working order and the bore is excellent with bright, sharp rifling. About the only detractor is a so-so magazine that could use an upgrade, but that's a very minor issue. This is a very collectible 1911A1 and one of the most desirable of all WWII pistols. A great example!

title: For Sale:  Antique Flobert .22 short Gallery or Parlor Rifle - Fires from an OPEN BOLT!
postcontent: I have the really nice example of an antique Flobert parlor gun in nice working condition. It has a nice walnut stock, 23" octagon barrel, front and rear peep sights, steel buttplate, and ornate iron trigger guard. The gun functions as it should, and is fun to shoot! I would recommend that you only shoot low-pressure "CB" shorts in it, as even these rounds probably exceed the original black powder proofs for that rifle. That being said, the barrel is quite thick with no flaws that I can see. It's smooth bore, so you could also shoot shot shells.   What makes this rifle unique is the firing design. Breach block cocks back and is released with the trigger.  The round fires when the block closes... the fireing pin is part of the block. It's foolproof, simple and quite interesting! It's been a great little keepsake, but now it's time to move it to someone else who can cherish it. I live near Mt Vernon, Burlington, Sedro-Woolley, and can meet you near I-5. This gun was made prior to 1898, so it can be sold direct without any transfer. I will need to see ID though. I could also ship it straight to your door.   Sorry, but I'm not really interested in any trades (never hurts to ask though!), and the price is firm.Thanks for looking, and have a great day!

postcontent: A very interesting revolver that will be great in your collection.  It has a WWII Flaming Bomb on Grip strap, then then an Austrian Police on the side. I'm told by another Armslister that this was probably post WWII, when the US gave a bunch of these and M1 Carbines to the Austrian Police.  There's also a bunch of numbers and vaious proofs stamped from all over.   It looks like the revolver was originally made for foreign contract prior to 4/24/42, before the Victory serial numbers started.
